Note

this is a simple process but requires sensitivity in terms of operating. since the entire plant is a liquid based system.

  • to boost the octane and cetane numbers, CR is used. the specification of petrol and diesel is different from what it was 50-60 years ago. to meet the specifications for environmental damage control, CR has gained importance.
  • additives used- toluene, benzene. previously used was TEL which is heavily poisonous due to lead.
  • CR converts Paraffin and naphthenes to high ON aromatic components. it produces
    1. H2
    2. LPG
    3. BTX
    4. High ON motor gasoline blending stock
  • environmental specifications (TEL, lighter Feed-stock burning)
  • Growth in petrochemical markets due to production of BTX
  • since H2 is produced -> clean fuels (removal of sulphur based impurities)
  • reformer has a very sensitive catalyst and requires a 100% sulphur free feed.

2. pure components in CR feed

  • C6 feed in naphtha -> producing aromatics.
  • C5 - C9 feed

3. reactions in FCC

  1. de-hydrogenation of naphthenes to aromatics
  2. isomerization of paraffin to naphthenes
  3. de-hydro-cyclisation of paraffin to aromatics

3.1 desirable reactions

3.1.1 isomerization

  • reversible
  • mildly exothermic
  • equilibrium is steadily attained
  • nowadays a division between CR units for separating isomerization and hydrogenation units.

3.1.2 de-hydrogenation

3.1.3 de-hydro-cyclization

(write from Chemistry of petrochemicals)
page 75

3.2 adverse reactions

3.2.1 hydro-cracking

  1. highly exothermic
  2. decrease in reformate yield

3.2.2. de-hydro-alkylation

3.2.3. coking

  1. low hydrogen can promote
  2. low pressure
  3. low C/H2 ratio

4. types of reformers

  1. semi-regenerative (regeneration of catalyst is necessary every 6-8 months, but the acts like a fixed bed) ]
  2. cyclic
  3. moving bed (pellets are used, not powder unlike FCC, regeneration and reactor cycles)

5. heat of reactions

reaction heat of reaction

6. process variables

  1. Reaction temperature
    • increase in octane
    • decrease yield
    • decrease hydrogen purity
    • increase coke deposit
  2. Space velocity (aka reciprocal of residence time)
    • L.H.S.V. and W.H.S.V.
    • reforming L.H.S.V. 1-3 l/hr
    • same effects as previous
  3. Reaction pressure
    • 3- 35 bar gauge (once designed for a specific pressure, you cannot change the operating pressure much)
    • decreasing pressure, increases dehydrogenation of naphthene
    • flavors aromatics and hydrogenation production
  4. Hydrogen/Hydro carbon ratio
    • to increase hydrogen partial pressure in the reaction
  5. Feed quality
    • N+ 2A is used to judge the feed quality is good for CR or not, where N is naphthene and A is aromatics.
    • heavy naphtha is thus better (i.e. C 7-C 9 fractions)
reccomended range

benzene 60-90 °
Toluene 90-110 °
Xylene 110-140 °
Octane blending stock greater than 140 °

7. catalyst fundamentals

  1. activity
  2. selectivity
  3. stability
  4. regenerability
  5. for a catalysts all these properties are not independent of each other. usually people are bound by feed stock availability.

7.1 catalysts

catalyst composition % wt
metal promoters like Ir, Re, Ge and Sn 0.003-0.7
metal Pt 0.2-0.6

7.4 catalyst selection

7.5 benefits of bi metallic over mono metallic catalyst

  1. enhanced resistance to coking
    1. lower fouling
    2. higher coke tolerance
    3. longer cycle length for s.r. unit
  2. low pressure and low H/Hydro Carbon operation
  3. better regenerability - i.e. extent to which the regenerated catalyst gived the original activity
  4. better ultimate life
  5. better yield stability

7.6 poisons

7.6.1 temporary poisons

poison tolerance limit ppm action
sulphur 0.5-1 burning
nitrogen 0.5-1 burning
chlorine 0.5
water 5

7.6.1.1 sulphur

effects

  • inhibits metal function
  • decrease hydrogen yield
  • recycle purity decrease
    reason
  • poor operation of pre-treater
    detection
  • draeger tubes-chromatographic setup, has sieves giving the color change
